Macedonians vote in a referendum on whether to change the name of the country
The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether to change their country’s name to “Republic of North Macedonia”, which would settle a long-standing dispute with Greece, which blocked its applications for accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes the province of Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbor is a claim to its territory, and has vetoed its accession to NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments concluded an agreement based on a proposal for a new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority of the Macedonian population.
President George Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum, and the boycott campaign questioned whether voter turnout would meet the minimum of 50 percent required for the referendum.
The question raised in a referendum was: “Do you support membership in NATO and the EU subject to the adoption of a treaty with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged after the collapse of Yugoslavia, should pay this price for joining organizations such as the EU and NATO.
“I came here today to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that it can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” says 79-year-old Olivera Georgievskaya, a resident of Skopje.
Sufficient members of parliament said they would abide by the results of the vote to make it decisive, although it does not have binding legal force.
The change of name would require a two-thirds majority of the members of parliament.
The State Election Commission said no reports of violations had been received by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16 percent compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place in Europe,” says 62-year-old Yose Tanevski, a voter from the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dusko voted in favour of a referendum in Macedonia on the question of changing the name of the country, which will pave the way for its accession to NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament building in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small scene, placing chairs in front of tents set up by those citizens who are going to boycott the referendum.
“We are for membership in NATO and the EU, but we want to unite with a high head, rather than exceeding the thresholds of official cabinets,” Kavadarkov said.
“Yes, we are citizens of a poor country, but we also have a sense of self-worth.
If they don’t want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring investments to Macedonia, which is so much needed in this country, where the unemployment rate is more than 20 percent.
“I believe the overwhelming majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens support the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after the vote.
He believes that a positive response will be “a guarantee of our prosperous future.”
A poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Political Studies showed that 30 to 43 percent of voters would take part in the referendum, but that is below the required turnout.
In another survey conducted by Macedonian channel Telecom-TV, it was found that 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy per cent of those respondents said they would vote in favour.
For a referendum to take place, attendance must be 50 percent plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum will be the first serious blow to the pro-Western government’s policy since it came to power in May last year.
