John Edwards: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was confirmed once again in 2018: outstanding exam results demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 students are educated throughout Scotland, aiming to provide the highest level of services to students and their parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen careers, as well as for the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the educational sector that is responsible for the development and implementation of an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, you call to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you turn to his heart.”
This is a convincing proof that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams this year, we see that languages occupy the leading positions in the league tables and have the highest score on the results of the exams in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade "A".
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received “A” in Mandarin (Chinese pronunciation), while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received “A”.
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Language subjects are now in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 percent of the reasons employers struggled to fill vacancies were a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require knowledge of languages, these skills are necessary in a globalized world.
Regardless of the profession the student will choose, if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will benefit him throughout his further life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit percentage, with 15 percent of the respondents speaking it.
That’s why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowing several languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will give children more chances of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland there is a fairly large disparity in terms of the languages that are taught - each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered most important to the UK in light of the country’s future development by 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with teaching staff, whose members are experts in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland strive to create a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future awaits them.
At present, there is no denying that languages remain vital in the global business environment for the future development of the country and should therefore be appropriately reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “skills of international communication.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits to Scotland’s youth.
We have to do it.
John Edwards, Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
