Harvard Students Learn to Rest on Special Courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, helped all elementary school students learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinistic culture of continuous caffeine consumption in order to wake up “at night in the spring.”
One of the academics found that the world’s most successful students often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chassler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he embarked on the idea of introducing such a course by presenting a preliminary report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl came up to me and said, ‘It’s a pity that I only learned about it now that I’m almost finishing my studies.’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was found that students were experiencing severe sleep deprivation during the school week.
The class lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections of the lesson, an image of a room in a dormitory is offered, where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, exercisers and books, get information about how each of these actions and substances — coffee, light, which both cause a lack of sleep — affect the number of sports results, and how important it is to get.
In another section, participants will learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
An interactive map of the campus encourages course participants to reflect on their daily life.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, like any other person has the right to know about, for example, how smoking affects their health,” Chassler said.
According to him, the false sense of pride that a person can “walk all night” is still widespread enough, and modern technology, as well as increasing pressure on students, means that sleep deprivation becomes a problem.
According to him, a sufficient amount of good quality sleep is a “secret weapon” for the student to fight stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to fight overweight, as insomnia translates the brain into a mode of starvation, causing him to constantly experience a feeling of hunger.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Chassler develop the course by attending one of the classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all graduate students to undergo a similar curriculum before enrolling in a competitive educational institution.
Professor Chassler recommends that students install an alarm clock that warns you that you need to go to bed and wake up, as well as remember the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupts the human biorhythm and leads to problems with sleepiness.
