The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet for Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that claims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on the open Berners-Lee Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people to give access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt’s goal was to gain “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he says of his startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “personal online data stores” or PODs.
It may contain contact lists, tasks, as well as a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools for dealing with data.
The app works on the same principle as Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify – all can be used in one browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of the personal online storage is that it is fully managed by the user, who can access any necessary information.
The company calls this principle “the personal empowerment through data.”
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea of Inrupt is that the company has provided the resources, processes and relevant skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several full-time developers with whom it has contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, tech developers around the world will be able to build their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not negotiating with Facebook and Google about whether his company is worth making drastic changes that will change all of their business models overnight.
“We don’t ask for their permission.”
In a post on Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that “the mission of Inrupt is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating a World Wide Web consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee’s voice has sounded quite influential in the debate over net neutrality.
Even launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Internet Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Internet,” says Berners-Lee.
