The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new study conducted at a site in the Scottish Highlands aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the obtained data will allow a new look at the behavior of unique winged mammals and help in further activities on the conservation of the species.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland, will examine the common bats, soprano bats, as well as the brown long-haired bats and bats of Dobanton, inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special registrars will be installed at certain points around the site to track the actions of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile field surveys using handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the types of activities that are responsible for the different groups of these animals.
A map of the habitat will then be drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes that these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the main areas of work on habitat management, such as the formation of meadows, as well as ways to maintain forest massifs in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are in danger of disappearing due to construction and development work that affects their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can pose a danger, as well as adhesive tape for flies, chemical processing of building materials and hunting domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to accurately identify obstacles along the flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat population issues very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, exit checks, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization even created Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten species of Scottish bats.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threave is a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings, lots of old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need for a prosperous existence.”
It reminds of the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance within private properties, as the unintentional destruction of one nest can result in the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire local population.
Flying mice are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat conservation officer, is calling on the public to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many of their individual species live,” she says.
